<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25045g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25045g">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25045g"> 45(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> resintaper (snob)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The candles that were used for ordinary lighting purposes seem to have been of three kinds: the dipped candle, which was made by taking a wick of flax, and dipping it again and again into melted grease until it had attained the necessary thickness; rushes may also have been used for wicks in this kind of candle; secondly, the rush-light candle, or rush <mark>taper</mark>, which was the light in everyday use; and, thirdly, the <mark>resin candle, called a snob</mark>, which was made by rolling resin in a soft state around a wick of linen rag. <small> J. F. M. Ffrench, <a name="JFPF" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#JFPF"><cite title="source">Prehistoric Faith and Worship</cite></a> (1912) 155</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c14024e" href="c14all.htm#c14024e">VI.C.14:024(e)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
